    <p>Solar panel installations in Virginia typically cost between \$2.30 to \$2.90 per watt before incentives, translating to \$11,500-14,500 for a 5kW system or \$23,000-29,000 for a 10kW system. After applying the 30% federal tax credit, these costs drop to \$8,050-10,150 for 5kW and \$16,100-20,300 for 10kW systems. Total costs include equipment, installation, permitting, and interconnection. Premium equipment and complex installations may cost more, while standard installations with quality equipment from established manufacturers often fall within these ranges. Financing options including solar loans and leases can reduce or eliminate upfront costs while still providing energy savings.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">What SEER rating is recommended for Virginia?</h3>
    <p>For Virginia's climate, HVAC systems with SEER ratings of 16 or higher are recommended to balance efficiency with cost-effectiveness. The federal minimum SEER requirement is 14 for new installations, but higher-efficiency systems provide better comfort and lower operating costs in Virginia's hot, humid summers. SEER 18-20 systems offer excellent efficiency for homeowners prioritizing maximum energy savings. Variable-speed systems often achieve higher effective efficiency than their SEER ratings suggest due to superior humidity control and part-load performance. Heat pumps should also have HSPF ratings of 9 or higher for optimal heating efficiency during Virginia's moderate winters.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">How long do solar panels last in Virginia?</h3>
    <p>Solar panels in Virginia typically last 25-30 years or longer with proper installation and maintenance. Most manufacturers provide 20-25 year performance warranties guaranteeing at least 80% of original output after two decades. Virginia's moderate climate is favorable for solar panel longevity, as extreme temperature cycling and severe weather events are relatively rare. Inverters typically require replacement after 10-15 years, while mounting systems and electrical components can last the lifetime of the solar installation. Regular cleaning and annual inspections help maximize system lifespan and performance.</p>
